Summarizing Data

Summarizing Data is very important! An overview of our data can help identifying common and/or unusual features of it. As you may already know, our data can be classified into two big types: Qualitative (or categorical), and Quantitative (or numeric). There are different techniques for summarizing data and it relies on the type of data we have.

Categorical Data

Categorical Data is a type of qualitative data that can be grouped into categories instead of being measured numerically. Reiterating what the textbook says:

The results can be the actual counts in each category, or they can be expressed as proportions or percentages

Summarizing and Plotting Categorical Data

The fun part begins! The first dataset that we will use is the students.csv that you can find attached. The fun part about this is that the different observations in this data are all of you! There are three variables:

  • section: Class section (categorical variable)
  • degreeProgram: Degree program (categorical variable)
  • classLevel: Class level (categorical variable)

Lets summarize this categorical data to answer some cool questions as which section has the highest enrollment, or how many different majors are enrolled in this class.

Lets say we want to know the number of students in each section.

First we use the table() function to create our frequency table. We will store the result in a new variable called section. The students$section means that we will be working with the column section in the students dataset.

# Making table
section <- table(students$section)

Once we created the variable section, we can see it just by typing it and running R!

# Printing the frequency table
section

We have an output! Our output looks like this:

Frequency table of different sections for STAT 703 Spring 2024
STAT 703 A STAT 703 ZA
33 53

The proverb A picture is worth a thousand words refers to the idea that one still image can sometimes communicate many different and often complex ideas. In this context, plots will be our best friends when summarizing/communicating our data analyses.

By typing the barplot() function you can generate a bar plot of the table we just created. Remember that the table created is stored under the variable name section.

# Constructing the barplot
barplot(section)

An alternative to barplots are pie charts. Just by typing the pie() function and running it you can create it yourself!

pie(section)

Try it yourself!

Numerical Data

Numerical Data is data that can be measured with numbers. Reiterating what the textbook says:

Numeric summaries can not only identify specific locations in the data (such as the average) but they can also quantify how disperse the values are.

Summarizing Numerical Data

In honor of our peeps from Nutrition, our second dataset will be the diets.csv that you can also find attached. This data is downloaded from kaggle, a website where you can find multiple datasets.

The diets.csv dataset consists of recipes from different diets and cuisine. It includes information on the macronutrients of each recipe. These are the 6 different variables:

  • Diet_type: The type of diet the recipe is for (categorical variable)
  • Recipe_name: The name of the recipe (categorical variable)
  • Cuisine_type: The cuisine the recipe is from (categorical variable)
  • Protein.g.: The amount of protein in grams (numerical variable)
  • Carbs.g.: The amount of carbs in grams (numerical variable)
  • Fat.g.: The amount of fat in grams (numerical variable)

Measures of location

The measures of location help us describe the central tendency of the data. These include the mean, median and mode. We can find the mean protein of the recipes in our dataset by using the mean() function. Dont forget that since we are interested in the protein, we must type the dataset$NameOfColumn, so diets$Protein.g.

# Calculating the mean for protein
mean(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 83.2315

We can also calculate the median by using the median() function

# Calculating the median for protein
median(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 56.28

Note how the mean for protein is greater than the median! What does it mean? It means that our protein is positively skewed, so that most of our values are clustered around the left tail of our distribution.

We can also check the quartiles by using the quantile() function. As a reminder, quartiles are values that divide a dataset into four equal parts. In this case, we are dividing the variable Protein.g. into the four equal parts.

# Calculating the quartiles for protein
quantile(diets$Protein.g.)
##        0%       25%       50%       75%      100% 
##    0.0000   24.4150   56.2800  112.3575 1273.6100

This means that we will find recipes from 0 grams of protein to 1273.61 grams of protein! Quite a wide range! Note how the 50% value is the same number as our median. This is because our second quartile (Q2) is the median of the dataset, representing the middle value when the data is ordered.

We can calculate the five-number summary and the mean by using the summary() function. Our output is similar to quantile. However, we have the mean included.

# Calculating five-number summary and mean for protein
summary(diets$Protein.g.)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00   24.41   56.28   83.23  112.36 1273.61

You can also find a certain percentile just by changing the quantile() function a little bit. Recall that percentiles are similar to quartiles but divide a dataset into 100 equal parts instead of just four. The pth percentile represents the value below which p percent of the data falls. So for example if we want to calculate the 40th percentile of the variable protein in the diets dataset, the 40th percentile (P40) would be the value below which 40% of the data falls. In this case: 41.67 grams of protein.

# Calculating the 40th percentile for protein
quantile(diets$Protein.g., probs = c(0.40))
##   40% 
## 41.67
Try it yourself!

Measures of dispersion

Measures of dispersion are statistical measures that describe how spread out or dispersed a set of data is. They provide insights into the variability or consistency of the data points. Some common measures of dispersion are range, IQR, variance, and standard deviation.

We can obtain the range for the variables Protein.g. and Fat.g. by using the range() function

# Calculating the range of protein
range(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1]    0.00 1273.61
# Calculating the range of fat
range(diets$Fat.g.)
## [1]    0.00 1930.24

Note that our range for protein has the same values as the 0th percentile and 100th percentile from above. It is a big range, but compared to fat, fat has a wider range!

A better way to measure variation is the interquartile range (IQR), which is the difference between the third quartile (Q3) and the first quartile (Q1). You can use the IQR() function or just subtract Q3 and Q1 by hand.

# using IQR function for protein and fat
IQR(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 87.9425
IQR(diets$Fat.g.)
## [1] 117.2225
# calculating IQR by hand for protein and fat
112.3575 - 24.4150
## [1] 87.9425
158.29 - 41.07
## [1] 117.22

You can see that by using the IQR, it seems that Fat.g. has a wider spread compared to Protein.g.

A more common way for measuring the variation is the variance (and standard deviation). Variance measures how far each data point in the set is from the mean and provides an average of the squared differences. The standard devation is just the squared root of the variance. You can use the functions var() and sd() correspondingly.

# variance for protein and fat
var(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 8063.552
var(diets$Fat.g.)
## [1] 14907.95
# standard deviation for protein and fat
sd(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 89.79728
sd(diets$Fat.g.)
## [1] 122.0981

This also shows that Fat.g. has a wider spread than Protein.g.

Try it yourself!

Outliers

Outliers are data points that significantly differ from the rest of the values in a dataset. Remember how our mean was higher than our mode for protein in our data? Our mean was influenced by possible outliers.

How can we identify outliers? We can identify them through various methods, such as visual inspection of graphs, statistical tests, or using specific criteria like being more than a certain number of standard deviations away from the mean.

Following the textbook, a high outlier has a value greater than the mean plus TWO standard deviations. Similarly, a low outlier has a value less than the mean minus TWO standard devations. Large datasets (like this), a high extreme outlier is greater than the mean plus THREE standard deviations. Similarly, a low extreme outlier is smaller than the mean minus THREE standard deviations.

Lets find some outliers in protein amount from the recipes, shall we?

# Calculating outliers
mean(diets$Protein.g.) + 2*sd(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 262.8261
mean(diets$Protein.g.) - 2*sd(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] -96.36307
# Calculating extreme outliers
mean(diets$Protein.g.) + 3*sd(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] 352.6233
mean(diets$Protein.g.) - 3*sd(diets$Protein.g.)
## [1] -186.1603

Recipes that have a protein amount of 262.82 grams or higher are considered high outliers. We have high outliers! Note that we dont have negative outliers since it is impossible to have negative values of protein in a meal. We also have high extreme outliers since we have recipes whom have 352.62 grams or more of protein. Our largest value for protein amount is 1273 grams, that is a high extreme outlier.

Graphs for numerical variables

Boxplots

The boxplot is also a graphical method used to represent the distribution of a set of data. You can create boxplots by using the boxplot() function.

# creating boxplot
boxplot(diets$Protein.g., horizontal = TRUE)

In this case, given that our variable is very skewed, we have a lot of dots. These dots are outliers and these values fell significantly outside the IQR range of the data.

Histograms

We can display the shape of a distribution with histograms. We can get it by using the hist() function.

# creating histogram
hist(diets$Protein.g.)

Scatterplots

This plot displays individual data points on a two-dimensional plane. Each point on the plot represents the values of two variables, making it a useful tool for visualizing correlation between them. You can use the plot() function. You must specify the x-axis and the y-axis. In this case, we will use Protein vs.Fat.

# creating scatterplot
plot(diets$Protein.g., diets$Fat.g.)

Due to the number of outliers and number of observations, it is a little bit difficult to find whether there is a correlation. However, it seems that there might be a slight positive correlation between these two.
